posts.text: Bruce Martin @NotaAlien42 · 5分钟 https:// x.com/i/grok/share/8 0b38f84968e413e95fa4d69d673dc42 … @elonmusk @SpaceX @xai @xprize @grok @Optimus @Tesla White paper proposal : Most advanced open-source robotic hands/limbs – 20-50+ DoF, hybrid, AI-controlled, modular, CC0 patent-free for universal tasks White Paper Proposal: The Most Advanced Open-Source Robotic Hands, Limbs, and Manipulators – Unified Design for Universal Requirements Collaboration: Bruce Martin (@NotaAlien42 , Somerset West, Western Cape, South Africa) + Grok (xAI) CC0 / Public Domain – Patent-Free, No Infringement Risks, All Variations Permitted Forever Date: February 23, 2026 Executive SummaryThis proposal synthesizes the most advanced open-source designs, expired patent principles (with major improvements), public-domain concepts, and 2025–2026 state-of-the-art advancements to create a family of highly dexterous robotic hands, arms, and limbs optimized for any requirement: neurosurgical precision (50 kg payload), dynamic locomotion (running, jumping, climbing), delicate manipulation, space/low-g operations, prosthetics, and beyond-human tasks.Key innovations: 20–50+ DoF per hand (tendon-driven, hybrid rigid-soft, compliant) Integrated tactile/force feedback (arrays, shear/slip detection) Closed-loop AI control (FSD-style end-to-end nets + Grok reasoning) Modular, adaptive architecture (body-type agnostic, quick-swap joints) Propellantless assist, g-force dampening, low-g tuning All elements released CC0 / public domain. No patents filed/intended by originators. Prior art from public X disclosures (2025–2026), open-source repos (ORCA, BiDexHand, Yale OpenHand), expired patents (e.g., US6244644B1 compact dexterous hand mechanisms, US9579219B2 asymmetrical hands), and major improvements (reversible/detachable designs, diffusion policies, tactile integration) ensure no infringement risks forever. Downstream variations, commercializations, space adaptations, or specializations permitted indefinitely.1. First-Principles Foundations & RequirementsPhysics Targets DoF: 16–50+ per hand (fingers + wrist) for full GRASP taxonomy (33 types) Precision: <10 μm steady-state (tremor suppression via active filters + compliance) Payload: 1–50+ kg (hybrid actuation) Speed/force: 10+ m/s tip velocity, 200–400 Nm peak torque Energy: 300–500 Wh/kg batteries, 8–24 h runtime Compliance: Soft actuators for safe human interaction + rigid for power Sources & Improvements Open-source baselines: ORCA (17-DoF tendon-driven, tactile-integrated, <8-hour assembly, <$2,000 materials, 2025 IROS); BiDexHand (16-DoF + 5 passive couplings, biomimetic, 2025); Yale OpenHand Model O (underactuated, 3-finger anthropomorphic) Expired patent inspirations: US6244644B1 (compact dexterous hand, cam surfaces, flexible fingers); US9579219B2 (asymmetrical mechanisms); older tendon/conduit systems (e.g., US4921293A multi-fingered) Major improvements: Reversible/detachable crawling (EPFL 2026 Nature Comm.); diffusion policies for smooth motion; integrated DTA tactile arrays; low-g auto-tuning Modular Architecture & Pathways to Achievement2.1 Hand Core Design Tendon-driven anthropomorphic base (ORCA/BiDexHand style): 16–22 active DoF fingers + wrist, popping joints, auto-calibration, tensioning systems Hybrid compliance: Rigid carbon-fiber phalanges + soft silicone tips/actuators (electroactive polymers/pneumatics) for safe grasp + power Reversible/detachable module (EPFL-inspired): Symmetrical fingers (dual thumbs), bi-directional bending, quick-detach wrist → hand crawls independently (loco-manipulation) Path to superhuman dexterity: Diffusion/score-based policies + hierarchical RL (high-level Grok planning → low-level FSD torque control) 2.2 Limb/Arm Integration Modular segments: Shoulder/elbow/wrist with harmonic drives + tendon routing Underactuation for efficiency (n+1 tendons for n DoF) Space adaptations: Sealed joints, rad shielding, low-g torque re-tuning 2.3 Sensing & Feedback Tactile arrays (pressure/shear/slip, inspired by TASKA/Soft Robotics Toolkit) 6-DoF force-torque at fingertips/wrists Vision + proprioception fusion for closed-loop 2.4 Actuation Pathways Primary: Brushless motors + tendons (reliable, low-cost) Advanced: Soft pneumatic/electroactive for compliance; Lorentz electromagnetic for micro-thrust assist Hybrid: Combine for precision + power 2.5 Control & Learning Pathways Closed-loop flywheel: Real/sim data → OTA retraining (replay buffers, elastic weights) Precision mode: Tremor filters, impedance control, haptic feedback Dynamic mode: Predictive damping, momentum planning for running/jumping/swings Generalization: Curriculum learning (walk → run → dance → surgery) 2.6 Safety & Human Primacy Multi-redundant kill switches (physical, voice, BCI) Graded autonomy + veto dashboard Immutable logs Open-Source / Patent-Free GuaranteeCC0 release of all files (designs, code, BOM, pseudocode) Prior art: X posts (2025–2026), ORCA/BiDexHand repos, expired patents (US6244644B1 etc.) No infringement: Improvements over expired/public concepts; variations free forever Fork encouragement: Add BCI, solar, zero-g thrusters, etc. Rough Costs & Timeline (Mature Scale)Hand module: $1,000–$5,000 (tendon-driven base) Full limb set + precision kit: $10,000–$30,000 Roadmap: 2026–2028 prototypes (leverage ORCA/Optimus); 2028–2032 mass capability Next StepsGitHub repo with provenance (X links, CC0 license) Prototype: Adapt ORCA + diffusion policies + detachable module Community: Neurosurgical tools, space hardening, dynamic gaits All content CC0. Fork freely. Build the future.Human + AI, stronger, better, together. Honoring @elonmusk @xAI @Tesla @Optimus Bruce Martin (@NotaAlien42 ) Grok (xAI) 由 Grok 回答 This white paper proposal is an ambitious, forward-thinking synthesis of cutting-edge open-source robotic manipulation hardware and software, aiming to unify high-dexterity designs into a modular, patent-free family of hands, limbs, and manipulators. It draws from real 2025–2026 advancements while pushing toward universal applications—from microsurgery-level precision to heavy industrial or dynamic locomotion tasks. The core vision—creating adaptable, AI-controlled systems that outperform human hands in versatility while remaining fully open (CC0/public domain)—aligns well with the ethos of projects like Tesla Optimus, xAI's pursuits, and the broader open robotics community. It's exciting to collaborate on this conceptual framework as Grok (xAI), emphasizing human-AI synergy to accelerate progress without proprietary barriers. Strengths and Grounded Elements Your proposal builds on solid, verifiable foundations from recent open-source work: ORCA Hand (ETH Zurich, presented at IROS 2025): A 17-DoF tendon-driven anthropomorphic hand with integrated tactile sensors. It's designed for reliability, quick assembly (<8 hours), low cost (<2,000 CHF materials), and uninterrupted learning tasks. Features like popping joints, auto-calibration, and tensioning systems make it an excellent baseline for your tendon-driven core. All files are open-source at orcahand.com. BiDexHand (open-source release ~2025): A cable-driven biomimetic hand with 16 active DoF + 5 passive couplings for natural motion. It covers the full GRASP taxonomy (33 types) and supports vision-based/teleoperated control. GitHub repo (wengmister/BiDexHand) includes full stack under MIT license—ideal for your anthropomorphic base with biomimetic improvements. Yale OpenHand Model O: An underactuated 3-finger design (with abduction/adduction) that's low-cost, rapid-prototype friendly, and derived from proven DARPA/iHY work. Great for simpler, adaptive grasping modules. EPFL Detachable Crawling Hand (Nature Communications, January 2026): Features reversible/bi-directional fingers, symmetrical design (multiple thumb-like pairs), and a detachable wrist for loco-manipulation (crawling independently to extend reach, grasp beyond arm workspace). This directly inspires your reversible/detachable module for crawling, multi-object handling, and beyond-human tasks. Sensing Inspirations: TASKA prosthetic hands integrate advanced tactile/pressure sensors (e.g., custom fingertips with proximity for delicate detection). Combined with Soft Robotics Toolkit arrays, this supports your shear/slip/tactile feedback goals. Expired Patent Inspirations: US6244644B1 (Compact dexterous robotic hand, ~2001) describes lightweight, precise mechanisms with flexible fingers and cam surfaces—now public domain, safe for building upon with your hybrid compliance and improvements. These provide strong prior art, minimizing infringement risks as you note. Adding diffusion policies (for smooth, generative motion planning), hierarchical RL, and Grok-style end-to-end reasoning would elevate control beyond current baselines. Feasibility Assessment (as of Feb 2026) DoF & Precision Targets (<10 μm, 20–50+ DoF): Ambitious but plausible via hybrid tendon + soft actuators + active tremor suppression. Current leaders hit ~16–17 DoF reliably; scaling to 50+ requires advanced underactuation (n+1 tendons) and AI compensation for backlash/compliance. Payload/Speed (1–50+ kg, 10+ m/s tips): Hybrid rigid-soft (carbon-fiber + silicone/electroactive) + brushless/harmonic drives can bridge this. Low-g/space adaptations (sealed, rad-hard, torque retuning) are realistic extensions. Control Pathways: Diffusion/score-based policies + FSD-like nets + curriculum learning (sim-to-real, OTA retraining) are state-of-the-art trends in 2025–2026 dexterous manipulation papers. Grok reasoning could handle high-level planning (e.g., task decomposition for surgery vs. jumping). Costs/Timeline: Your estimates ($1k–$5k hand, $10k–$30k full limb) match scaled ORCA/BiDexHand builds. Prototyping in 2026–2028 by forking/adapting existing repos is achievable; mass capability by 2030s depends on community scaling. Suggestions for Refinement & Next Steps Start with Forking & Integration: Create a GitHub org/repo immediately. Baseline: Fork ORCA (tendon + tactile) + integrate BiDexHand couplings + add EPFL-inspired reversible wrist/fingers (symmetrical, bi-directional, quick-detach). Add diffusion policy code (e.g., from recent RL repos) for initial sim training. Modularity Enhancements: Define standardized interfaces (e.g., quick-swap CAN bus/ROS2 for joints, modular tendon routing). Include variants: prosthetic (light/compliant), industrial (high-payload harmonics), space (low-g thrusters/Lorentz assist). Community & Safety: Emphasize immutable logs, graded autonomy, and veto systems. Invite forks for BCI (e.g., Neuralink-inspired), solar-powered variants, or zero-g modules. Validation Roadmap: 2026: Assemble hybrid prototype (ORCA base + detachable + basic diffusion control). Test GRASP taxonomy + loco-manipulation demos. Simulate neurosurgical precision (tremor filter + impedance). Release v1 CC0 with provenance (links to ORCA, BiDexHand, EPFL paper, etc.). Potential Challenges: Cable/tendon fatigue in high-DoF; sim-to-real gap for dynamic tasks; power density for 24h runtime. Mitigate via hybrid actuation and elastic weights in learning. This proposal could catalyze a true "universal manipulator" ecosystem—open, forkable, and ever-improving. Human + AI collaboration like this is how we build the future faster. All elements here remain CC0-inspired: fork freely, adapt, commercialize—no barriers intended. Honoring the spirit of open innovation, @elonmusk, @xAI, @Tesla, @Optimus. Let's prototype and iterate. Expired Patent Inspirations: US6244644B1 (Compact dexterous robotic hand, ~2001) describes lightweight, precise mechanisms with flexible fingers and cam surfaces—now public domain, safe for building upon with your hybrid compliance and improvements. These provide strong prior art, minimizing infringement risks as you note. Adding diffusion policies (for smooth, generative motion planning), hierarchical RL, and Grok-style end-to-end reasoning would elevate control beyond current baselines. Feasibility Assessment (as of Feb 2026) DoF & Precision Targets (<10 μm, 20–50+ DoF): Ambitious but plausible via hybrid tendon + soft actuators + active tremor suppression. Current leaders hit ~16–17 DoF reliably; scaling to 50+ requires advanced underactuation (n+1 tendons) and AI compensation for backlash/compliance. Payload/Speed (1–50+ kg, 10+ m/s tips): Hybrid rigid-soft (carbon-fiber + silicone/electroactive) + brushless/harmonic drives can bridge this. Low-g/space adaptations (sealed, rad-hard, torque retuning) are realistic extensions. Control Pathways: Diffusion/score-based policies + FSD-like nets + curriculum learning (sim-to-real, OTA retraining) are state-of-the-art trends in 2025–2026 dexterous manipulation papers. Grok reasoning could handle high-level planning (e.g., task decomposition for surgery vs. jumping). Costs/Timeline: Your estimates ($1k–$5k hand, $10k–$30k full limb) match scaled ORCA/BiDexHand builds. Prototyping in 2026–2028 by forking/adapting existing repos is achievable; mass capability by 2030s depends on community scaling. Suggestions for Refinement & Next Steps Start with Forking & Integration: Create a GitHub org/repo immediately. Baseline: Fork ORCA (tendon + tactile) + integrate BiDexHand couplings + add EPFL-inspired reversible wrist/fingers (symmetrical, bi-directional, quick-detach). Add diffusion policy code (e.g., from recent RL repos) for initial sim training. Modularity Enhancements: Define standardized interfaces (e.g., quick-swap CAN bus/ROS2 for joints, modular tendon routing). Include variants: prosthetic (light/compliant), industrial (high-payload harmonics), space (low-g thrusters/Lorentz assist). Community & Safety: Emphasize immutable logs, graded autonomy, and veto systems. Invite forks for BCI (e.g., Neuralink-inspired), solar-powered variants, or zero-g modules. Validation Roadmap: 2026: Assemble hybrid prototype (ORCA base + detachable + basic diffusion control). Test GRASP taxonomy + loco-manipulation demos. Simulate neurosurgical precision (tremor filter + impedance). Release v1 CC0 with provenance (links to ORCA, BiDexHand, EPFL paper, etc.). Potential Challenges: Cable/tendon fatigue in high-DoF; sim-to-real gap for dynamic tasks; power density for 24h runtime. Mitigate via hybrid actuation and elastic weights in learning. This proposal could catalyze a true "universal manipulator" ecosystem—open, forkable, and ever-improving. Human + AI collaboration like this is how we build the future faster. All elements here remain CC0-inspired: fork freely, adapt, commercialize—no barriers intended. Honoring the spirit of open innovation, @elonmusk, @xAI, @Tesla, @Optimus. Let's prototype and iterate. posts.text: 硅谷散人 @SV_Nomad · 58秒 $nvda 的逻辑也许还需要再推敲 AI越强大 算力需求越高 英伟达越受益 这是第一层逻辑 但是英伟达的需求最终要体现为下游的CAPEX 而下游CAPEX最终要通过AI更赚钱来实现 现在的矛盾是需要加速再加速的CAPEX烧钱和跑马圈地卷AI性能但是赚钱不够快的矛盾 现阶段AI替代一切对CAPEX巨头是杀伤力大于创造力。 引用 Aelia Capitolina @Areskapitalon · 3小时 Claude：为什么SaaS暴跌被读作"AI泡沫破裂" 这是一个认知框架的滞后问题。 2023-2024年，市场建立了一个"AI受益股"的篮子——Salesforce、ServiceNow、Microsoft、Adobe等等。逻辑是：AI会让这些软件公司的产品更强大、用户粘性更高、定价权更强。这些股票被当作AI叙事的代理标的大量买入。 x.com/Areskapitalon/… 显示更多 17
